Principal Component Analysis

Dataset water.zostera.red.scaled

This dataset contains 28 individuals and 8 variables, 1 qualitative variable is considered as illustrative.

1. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of PCA express 64.02% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 64.02% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This percentage is relatively high and thus the first plane well represents the data variability. This value is greater than the reference value that equals 54.13%, the variability explained by this plane is thus significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 834 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a normal distribution).

From these observations, it should be better to also interpret the dimensions greater or equal to the third one.

Figure 1 - Decomposition of the total inertia on the components of the PCA

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 2 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (64.02% against 54.13%). This observation suggests that only these axis are carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

2. Description of the plane 1:2

Figure 2.1 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction.

The Wilks test p-value indicates which variable factors are the best separated on the plane (i.e. which one explain the best the distance between individuals).

##   station 
## 0.1573076

There only is one possible qualitative variable to illustrate the distance between individuals : station.

Figure 2.2 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction. The individuals are coloured after their category for the variable station.

Figure 2.3 - Variables factor map (PCA) The labeled variables are those the best shown on the plane.

Figure 2.4 - Qualitative factor map (PCA) The labeled factors are those the best shown on the plane.

The dimension 1 opposes individuals such as 1, 10, 5, 25 and 3 (to the right of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as 7, 26 and 2 (to the left of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individuals 1, 10, 5, 25 and 3 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables chl_a, PO4 and seston (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The group in which the individuals 7, 26 and 2 stand (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Ntotal, secchi and NO3 (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable seston.

The dimension 2 opposes individuals such as 7, 1, 10, 5, 25, 3, 26 and 2 (to the top of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as 19, 21, 6, 11 and 14 (to the bottom of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individuals 7, 26 and 2 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Ntotal, secchi and NO3 (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable seston.

The group in which the individuals 1, 10, 5, 25 and 3 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables chl_a, PO4 and seston (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The group in which the individuals 19, 21, 6, 11 and 14 stand (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • low values for the variables chl_a, Ntotal, NH4 and NO3 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

3. Classification

Figure 3 - Ascending Hierarchical Classification of the individuals. The classification made on individuals reveals 3 clusters.

The cluster 1 is made of individuals such as 2, 7, 18 and 26. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables Ntotal, NO3 and secchi (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable PO4.

The cluster 2 is made of individuals such as 6, 11, 14, 19 and 21. This group is characterized by :

  • low values for the variables chl_a, NH4, Ntotal and NO3 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The cluster 3 is made of individuals such as 1, 3, 5, 10 and 25. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables chl_a, PO4 and NH4 (variables are sorted from the strongest).
